UNIT II - Image Building & Container Management
1. Dockerfile Core Concepts

A Dockerfile is a script used to create Docker images.

Example
FROM openjdk:17
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
RUN javac Main.java
CMD ["java","Main"]

Build image:

docker build -t javaapp .
2. Image Layering

Each instruction creates a new layer.

FROM ubuntu
RUN apt update
RUN apt install nginx
COPY . /app

Each line = layer.

3. Build Context & .dockerignore
Build Context

Files sent to Docker daemon during build.

docker build .
.dockerignore

Used to exclude unnecessary files.

Example:

node_modules
.git
temp.txt
4. Dockerfile Instructions
FROM

Base image.

FROM ubuntu
RUN

Executes command during build.

RUN apt update
COPY

Copies local files.

COPY . /app
ADD

Like COPY + supports URL/tar extraction.

CMD

Default command.

CMD ["python","app.py"]
ENTRYPOINT

Fixed executable.

WORKDIR

Working directory.

WORKDIR /app
ENV

Environment variable.

ENV PORT=8080
EXPOSE

Expose port.

EXPOSE 8080
VOLUME

Create mount point.

VOLUME /data
5. Docker Build Process

Command:

docker build -t myapp:v1 .
Meaning
build = create image
-t = tag
. = current directory
6. Image Tagging / Versioning

Tags identify versions.

docker tag myapp:v1 myapp:latest

Examples:

v1
v2
latest
prod
7. Inspecting Images
View Images
docker images
Inspect Metadata
docker inspect nginx
View Layers / History
docker history nginx
8. Docker Networking

Docker supports networking between containers.

List Networks
docker network ls
9. Bridge Network

Default network for standalone containers.

docker run -d nginx

Containers communicate using bridge.

10. Host Network

Container uses host machine network directly.

docker run --network host nginx
11. Overlay Network

Used in multi-host/container orchestration like swarm.

Used to connect containers across multiple hosts.

12. DNS Inside Docker

Docker provides internal DNS.

Containers can communicate using container names.

Example:

docker run --name db mysql
docker run app

App can connect using hostname db

13. Linking Containers

Old method:

docker run --link db:mysql app

Now mostly replaced by custom networks.

14. Port Mapping

Map host port to container port.

docker run -p 8080:80 nginx

Meaning:

Host Port = 8080
Container Port = 80

Access in browser:

localhost:8080
15. Docker Storage

Containers are temporary. Data may be lost after removal.

Use volumes or bind mounts.

16. Volumes vs Bind Mounts
Feature	Volume	Bind Mount
Managed by Docker	Yes	No
Better Portability	Yes	No
Direct Host Path	No	Yes
Volume Example
docker run -v mydata:/data ubuntu
Bind Mount Example
docker run -v /home/user/data:/data ubuntu
17. Backing Data on Host

Store data permanently on host system using:

Volumes
Bind mounts
18. Copy-on-Write Mechanism

Docker saves changes only in writable layer.

Original image layers remain unchanged.

Benefit
Fast containers
Less storage
Efficient cloning
